Data description for the open dataset for human SSVEPs in the frequency range of 1-60 Hz:

We provide raw EEG data record in the format of Brain Imaging Data Structure (BIDS). The raw EEG data for each participant is organized within a designated folder (e.g., “sub-001”). The EEG is stored in “.edf” files, while the “.tsv” and “.json” files contain relevant information about the experiment.

Another type of segmented epoch data related to stimuli was captured, with each participant's data forming an independent MATLAB MAT file. Each file was named following the convention "data_Subject index_Number of channels" (e.g., data_s1_64.mat, data_s2_64.mat, ..., data_s30_64.mat). For each subject, the data was structured as a 5-dimensional matrix (condition × channel × time point × frequency × block). Specifically, the condition dimension has a size of 2, corresponding to two distinct modulation depths (Low-Depth and High-Depth). The number of channels is 64, and the names and locations of these channels can be found in the supplementary table 2. The time point duration is 5.14 s, representing a stimulation time of 5 s and a post-stimulation duration of 0.14 s. The stimulus frequency dimension consists of 60 levels, corresponding to stimulation frequencies ranging from 1 to 60 Hz. There are 12 blocks, indicating 12 repeated stimuli for each stimulus pattern. 

Note: In the EEG data for all participants, electrode connections for channels 33 ("M1') and 34 ("M2") of the 64-channel montage were identified as open circuits during the experiment.

Note: The trigger values for trials are divided into two ranges, corresponding to the "Low-Depth" and "High-Depth" stimulus paradigms:

Trigger values in the range of 31-45, 91-105, 151-165, and 211-225 respectively correspond to the Low-Depth stimulus paradigm in four sessions.
Trigger values in the range of 46-60, 106-120, 166-180, and 226-240 respectively correspond to the High-Depth stimulus paradigm in four sessions.

The stimulus frequencies for each session are as follows:

In the first session, the stimulus frequencies include 1, 5, 9, ... up to 57 Hz.
In the second session, the stimulus frequencies include 2, 6, 10, ... up to 58 Hz.
In the third session, the stimulus frequencies include 3, 7, 11, ... up to 59 Hz.
In the fourth session, the stimulus frequencies include 4, 8, 12, ... up to 60 Hz.